message.content: We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The symptom of pain when the shoulder is externally rotated against resistance is indicative of rotator cuff tendinitis. Among the options, only the infraspinatus tendon is a member of the rotator cuff.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The infraspinatus muscle is responsible for external rotation of the shoulder, and an injury to its tendon would cause pain with this movement. The other options do not contribute significantly to external rotation of the shoulder.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The pain with external rotation against resistance suggests injury to the infraspinatus tendon, which is involved in external rotation of the shoulder. Teres major and pectoralis major are not involved in external rotation, and supraspinatus is typically involved in abduction of the shoulder, not external rotation.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The external rotation against resistance narrows down the possible tendons involved to infraspinatus and teres minor. Infraspinatus is more commonly injured in overhead sports such as baseball. Pectoralis major is involved in adduction and flexion of the shoulder, while supraspinatus is commonly involved in rotator cuff injuries.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The fact that the pain is reproduced when the shoulder is externally rotated against resistance suggests an injury to the infraspinatus tendon. The teres major and pectoralis major are not typically involved in this type of injury, and while supraspinatus injuries can also cause shoulder pain, they typically involve pain when the arm is raised above the head.

The teres major and pectoralis major are not commonly associated with shoulder pain, and supraspinatus injuries usually result in pain during abduction of the shoulder.

The teres major and pectoralis major do not have a direct role in shoulder external rotation, and supraspinatus is usually associated with pain during abduction.

The location and mechanism of pain reproduction suggest that the most likely injured tendon is the infraspinatus, which is responsible for external rotation of the shoulder. The teres major and pectoralis major are involved in internal rotation and adduction of the shoulder, respectively. The supraspinatus is involved in abduction of the arm.

Teres major and pectoralis major do not have much involvement in external rotation of the shoulder. Injury to supraspinatus tendon usually results in pain during abduction of the shoulder.
